The "Order of Operations" [Step by Step flow]
For a trade to settle successfully, the order must be "registered" in the repository before the matching happens. Here is the correct sequence:

The Request: Postman sends a "BUY AAPL" request.

The Check: RiskManager checks the Wallet to make sure the user has enough cash.

The Registration (CRITICAL): You call orderRepository.save(order). Now the system "knows" this order ID belongs to "User1".

The Matching Engine: The order goes into the OrderBook algorithm.

The Match: The algorithm finds a "SELL AAPL" order that was already in the repo. It generates a Trade.

The Settlement: The settleTrade method takes that Trade and asks the Repo: "Who owns the orders in this trade?"

The Hand-off: Because you did Step 3, the Repo says: "Order A belongs to User1, and Order B belongs to User2."

The Bank: The WalletService finally moves the money and shares.



---- Trade in it -----
[OrderBook receives the whole Order object, but inside the Matching Algorithm, it ignores the userId entirely. It only looks at:

 Price: To see if the buyer and seller can agree.

 Quantity: To see how much can be traded.

 Timestamp: To decide who was first in line (Price-Time Priority).]



  When the Matching Engine finishes, it creates a Trade object. That trade object looks like this:

  buyOrderId: "abc-123"

  sellOrderId: "xyz-789"

  price: 150

  quantity: 10

  When this trade is sent to Settlement, the first thing the code does is:
  orderRepository.findById("abc-123")




